(In reply to comment #20) > I don't think this has to do with the initialization info or flow analysis. Had > it been the case, this would have cause VerifyError with a 1.6 JRE also, but > currently the code runs fine with 1.6, even without using "UseSplitVerifier" > option.
Not sure what this proves.
If the code is compiled for 1.6, then a JVM of any vintage is allowed to silently fall back to the old verification scheme. That may explain why it runs fine with 1.6 JRE.
(There is an option to tell the JVM to not fall back - - XX:-FailOverToOldVerifier, but this is rejected for some reason. In our own tests, we run it with an option that says don't allow for fall back I am not able to dig up the string right now)
Note that this failover mechanism is triggered by the class file version not the JRE used.
So it is not clear we can assert "this has nothing to do with the initialization info or flow analysis." ?(In reply to comment #20)
> The earliest version I can reproduce this is 3.7.1, since thats when Java 7 > support came out.
That is not what I meant - If you compile with 3.6 and look at the stack map table - does it look alright ? Was there a point in time when it was fine and then went bad ? I agree the manifestation have started only with 3.7.1 since a JRE7 VM is not allowed to fall back (against a 1.7 class file)

Let us continue to investigate - bottom line, we can't yet discount problems with initialization information or flow analysis. Most of these stack shape problems directly result from incorrect range calculated by the compiler.

I'm wondering if this is a good strategy: in org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.MethodScope.recordInitializationStates(FlowInfo) , look at the local variables declared in the current scope and record the maximum id found. Now from the flowInfo's definiteInits, reset all inits in bit positions after this id (since they correspond to locals declared in inner scopes), and use this modified inits info to calculate the state index.

OK, so this is not near a solution but let me share anyway:
At the end of Block.analyseCode I try to find which locals get out of scope and reset the corresponding definits.
The implementation is crude, implementing this logic: - inspect all locals defined in this scope - check if any parent scope as a local with the same ID remove all now-unused IDs from definits (only for UnconditionalFlowInfo for now)

Created attachment 216188 test & fix v1
This is the first version that could potentially be considered as a fix.
I replaced the assumably expensive implementation of Block.exitScope() with a variant where this information is collected as we go.
This is achieved using new fields in BlockScope:
public long ownedLocals = 0L; mask of ids of local variables directly owned by this scope
public long parentOwnedLocals = 0L; accumulated mask of ids of all local variables owned by parent scopes
public boolean isExiting = true; flag used by ForStatement to signal that exitScope() must be deferred.
Obviously the two long masks need to be accompanied with bit sets for ids > 64 :(
Handling only UnconditionalFlowInfo is another incompleteness.
All these seem to be easily fixable.
At this point I'm taking a break to wait for comments.
Would anybody want to test the fix against the original sources?

More results from running all JDT/Core tests and from discussing with Ayush an alternative implementation:
- *all* calls to Block.exitScope() must check if scopes are the same, check should be pulled into that method (was a regression in DebugEvaluationTest.test017())
- the field BlockScope.parentOwnedLocals doesn't save much, addLocalVariable may as well loop over the parent chain.
However: getting the bit masks in the expected shape is tricky: If we want to maintain BlockScope.ownedLocals in a shape that can be directly used for resetting bits in the flow info, than we need to know the maxFieldOffset. This, however, may not be available in its final form during BlockScope.addLocalVariable() because TypeDeclaration.updateMaxFieldCount doesn't run before analyseCode (hadn't we cleaned up this part in the work on null analysis for fields?).
I still think we could follow that road, but that's certainly not for Juno.
If we want something with minimal risks, I agree with Ayush that using the existing FlowInfo.resetAssignmentInfo() would be best:
PRO: minimal code changes, i.e., minimal risk to break anything
CON: slightly more expensive (looping over all local variables rather than resetting bits in a combined bit set operation).

So from my p.o.v. this patch is ready to go, pending just a final run of all JDT/Core tests (plus other ways of testing).
I would suggest to include this for RC3 based on this assessment:
- the compiler generates invalid byte code - older VMs silently accept the wrong attribute - the issue will become relevant as people migrate to a Java7 VM, which needs explicit parameters to accept the wrong attribute => this will be perceived as a regression
- the patch is simple and well localized to perform only one simple task: - remove assignment information about local variables when exiting their declaring scope / block. - the lack of doing so has been identified as causing the bug in the stack map attribute - this change has no impact on the rest of flow analysis, because the assignment information is unused beyond that point anyway.
Although I previously discussed potential performance impact of the implementation the impact will certainly not be big: - the nested loop I was seeing before could be eliminated in comment 40. - we do use multiple calls to FlowInfo.resetAssignmentInfo instead of combining all changes into one bit set operation, but unless a scope has a huge number of local variables (say: hundrets) this is perfectly within the bounds of what flow analysis does anyway.

So we have ForStatement (bug 359495), Block (this bug) and TWR (this bug) which all can declare a local variable (and need to be cleaned-up after).
But then: why is ForeachStatement not affected (or is it)? When trying to construct a failing test I see that the elementVariable is marked as only potentially initialized after the statement, probably because the collection could be empty and thus the elementVariable never gets assigned. If the stackmap is only affected by definits, not potinits than this would make the ForeachStatement case safe, but it's not that obvious why it's different from "for" and "twr".
Moreover, ForeachStatement.analyseCode() contains one branch, where a definit *would* get through, but it seems to be unreachable for "good" code: If we ever reach line 135: exitBranch = condInfo.initsWhenFalse(); *and* produce runnable byte code, it should be possible to also get this stackmap problem here. This is *probably* impossible, but this isn't "obviously safe" either, I'd say.
At least I suggest adding a comment near "this.mergedInitStateIndex =" in ForeachStatement.analyseCode().
